REASONING: GDP per capita can be measured in different ways (nominal vs PPP), which can change the rankings. As Wikipedia explains: "Comparisons of GDP per capita are also frequently made on the basis of purchasing power parity (PPP), to adjust for differences in the cost of living in different countries"

On the commonly cited nominal GDP per capita (IMF estimates), Luxembourg is highest, not Singapore. The IMF-ranked table shows: "Luxembourg 140,941 2025" (IMF estimate at the top of the table), indicating Singapore is not the highest on this measure.

On a PPP basis, the CIA World Factbook ranks Singapore first for 2024 estimates: "1 Singapore $132,600 2024 est. 2 Luxembourg $128,200 2024 est." This shows the claim can be true only under a specific definition (PPP) and source.

Because the claim does not specify the metric, it is not universally true. Under nominal GDP per capita (IMF), Singapore is not the highest. Therefore, as stated without qualification, the claim is misleading/incorrect.
